item.title: Our Ingredients
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
[vc_row][vc_column width="1/2"][vc_column_text]

OUR INGREDIENTS

[/vc_column_text][vc_tta_accordion active_section="1" css=".vc_custom_1442573667171{padding-bottom: 50px !important;}"][vc_tta_section title="Flour" tab_id="1442324969483-95862999-dee1"][vc_column_text css_animation="left-to-right"]The English word for "flour" is originally a variant of the word "flower". Both derive from the Old French fleur or flour, which had the literal meaning "blossom", and a figurative meaning "the finest".[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="Yeast" tab_id="1442324969557-1641651a-934b"][vc_column_text css_animation="left-to-right"]Yeasts are chemoorganotrophs, as they use organic compounds as a source of energy and do not require sunlight to grow. Carbon is obtained mostly from hexose sugars, such as glucose and fructose, or disaccharides such as sucrose and maltose.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="Eggs" tab_id="1442324997068-10c805bb-9cf8"][vc_column_text css_animation="left-to-right"]Egg yolks and whole eggs store significant amounts of protein and choline, and are widely used in cookery. Due to their protein content, the United States Department of Agriculture categorizes eggs as Meats within the Food Guide Pyramid.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][/vc_tta_accordion][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/2"][vc_single_image image="82" img_size="full" alignment="right" css_animation="right-to-left"][/vc_column][/vc_row]
